@endnode

@node Contents "Contents"

   This archive should contain the following files:

        3DPie.dsrx                - Script to draw a 3D pie chart
        3DPieDemo.IFF             - Demo picture for the 3D pie char script
        3DPieDemo.IFF.info        - 3D pie chart demo picture's icon
        PieDataFile               - Example data file for 3D Pie script
        NewBarGraph.dsrx          - Improved version of the bar graph script
        NewBarGraphDemo.IFF       - Demo picture of the bar graph script
        NewBarGraphDemo.IFF.info  - Bar graph demo picture's icon
        BarDataFile               - Example data file for new bar graph script
        LineGraph.dsrx            - Script to draw a line graph
        LineGraphDemo.IFF         - Demo picture of the line graph script
        LineGraphDemo.IFF.info    - Line graph demo picture's icon
        LineDataFile              - Example data file for line graph script
        Table.dsrx                - A script that draws a table of data
        TableDemo.IFF             - Demo picture of the table script
        TableDemo.IFF.info        - Table demo picture's icon
        NewGrid.dsrx              - Modified grid script
        NewGridDemo.IFF           - Demo picture for grid script
        NewGridDemo.IFF.info      - Grid demo picture's icon
        DSMiscRexxVol3.Guide      - This file
        DSMiscRexxVol3.Guide.info - This file's icon

   If for any reason it doesn't, this program can be downloaded from the
Aminet (or obtained from an Aminet CD) in the util/rexx directory as
DSMiscRexxVol3.lha.

@endnode

@node Brief "Brief description of the scripts"

The scripts are easily installed by simply selecting "All Files" from the
"Show" sub-menu in the "Window" menu on Workbench with the window
containing this document selected. Just drag all the files ending in .dsrx
over to the "Rexx" drawer in your DrawStudio folder or disc. It's that
easy! If, however you are already running DrawStudio, you'll have to wait
until the next time you load the program before you can use the scripts.

IMPORTANT! Some of these scripts require rexxmathlib.library (available
from Aminet sites at util/rexx/RexxMathLib.lha or on Aminet CD 16).

Before you read about the scripts, why not have a quick peek at the demo
pictures I have included along with the scripts ? If English isn't your
first language, then you might find the pictures a little more helpful.
Anyway, this is what they do...

Although some of these scripts are fairly elaborate, well-programmed they
ain't. They're not exactly smart, so some things may well throw the scripts
(for example, negative values in the graph scripts). I've always found ARexx
programming a rather disturbing and undesirable thing, because for me it's
like airing your dirty laundry in front of everyone else. At least with C,
Assembly language, or AMOS you can tuck away your slightly
less-than-unorthodox programming techniques away from the sneers and sniggers
of others (unless of course they're the sort of person who has no life and
goes sifting through other people's code with a copy of Enforcer and MonAm,
looking for things to criticise). ARexx isn't like that. Ho hum.

Unfortunately, I have found that some of DrawStudio's operations have a
tendency to be a bit temperamental at times. I should warn you that
apart from possible problems with the scripts themselves, some may
occasionally behave unpredictably. The most common problem is loss of
attributes. This is shown by objects which suddenly either have dotted
line style for no reason or no visible line at all. The scripts attempt
to work around this by forcing attributes into the objects, but they may
not work. Be warned!

* 3DPie       - This is one of the prettiest scripts you'll find in this
                particular volume. As the name suggests, it will produce
                a simple 3D pie chart based upon a set of values it
                reads in from a file (an example file has been provided).
                As for the 2D version, you are able to pick up individual
                slices and move them about, and they are drawn in such a
                way that you will see a complete slice in three
                dimensions when you pull it away. These pie charts are
                particularly effective with translucent fills, as shown
                in the demo picture.

                You can set the width and height of the top of the pie chart
                by changing PIESIZEX and PIESIZEY respectively. The
                location of the chart on the page is set using CENX and
                CENY, but note that these are measured from the centre
                of the graph. The depth of the chart is set using
                PIEDEPTH. It's presently set to 1 centimetre, which
                gives a reasonble result. Should you wish to increase
                this value, bear in mind that significantly taller pie
                charts will look very odd owing to the fact that the
                curve at the bottom of the graph should be deeper.
                There's some perspective-related artistic reason for
                this, and you can see the effect for yourself if you set
                PIEDEPTH to a large value (like 15 cm). Finally, as the
                chart is drawn starting from 180° (ie. at the bottom),
                going anti-clockwise, it is conceivable that you may
                wish drawing to start from a different angle. By making
                PIEANG greater than zero, you can rotate the entire pie
                chart anti-clockwise by whatever angle you wish.

                Note: When you're running this script, be warned that it will
                start looking for a data file. Chances are the location of
                this file will be different when you install the scripts and
                so you'll need to modify the script to reflect this. It's not
                a hard thing to do. Simply look for the line which says
                DATAFILE = "Dh0:T/DSMiscRexxVol3/PieDataFile" and modify the
                contents of the quotes accordingly. Dead easy!

* NewBarGraph - This is a significantly improved version of the original
                histogram script. Just like the 3D Pie chart script it will
                read values in from a file, but this time it will also
                label both the axis and draw the values on the vertical
                scale. After it was requested, I have also added support
                for standard error bars (for those that know what they
                are and how they're used -note that I am not among
                them!). To make things a little more intuitive, the
                script will now group common elements together (eg. the
                bars, and the scales) to make colouring them much easier.
                You can also apply a grid to either or both the axis.

                You can set the location of the graph on the page by
                setting the OFFSETX and OFFSETY variables to appropriate
                values (in centimetres). Please note that these set the
                position from the horizontal origin and the top of the
                graph, so if you set OFFSETX too small, you'll find that
                the labels will end up off the page. Use FITSIZEX and
                FITSIZEY to set the size of the graph, but again these
                values only apply to the graph itself, not the ticks and
                labels. If you wish to move the horizontal or vertical
                origin away from the edge of the graph, get LINEGAPX and
                LINEGAPY, however some of the more pedantic people on
                the receiving end of such a graph tend to complain
                bitterly about origins which don't touch the edges. The
                length of the ticks on horizontal and vertical scales
                can be altered by changing TICKSIZEX and TICKSIZEY. The
                distance between the actual axis values and the ticks
                can be set by tweaking LABELGAPX and LABELGAPY. The
                distance between these and the axis titles can be set
                with TITLEGAPX and TITLEGAPY. You can apply a grid to
                the X or Y axis by setting XGRID or YGRID to 1. Setting
                them to zero doesn't draw a grid. This grid can be drawn
                in front of or behind the graph, by setting FRONTGRID
                appropriately. Set it to 1 to bring it to the front. The
                distance between each bar can be set using the GAP
                variable. By increasing this value, the bars are more
                spaced out, in many cases making the graph look less
                cluttered. Finally, you can set whether or not the
                actual bars are defined as what DrawStudio calls a
                "compound object" or simply a group. At the simplest
                level, the distinction is simply whether to apply a
                fill to each bar individually ("group" mode) or fill the
                bars as if they were a complete object ("compound"
                mode). If you're using gradient fills, compound bars
                tend to look more attractive. If you've got a vertical
                gradient, compound bars make the gradient stretch from
                the tallest bar on the graph to the bottom (as shown in
                the example). With grouped bars, there is a different
                gradient for each bar, and so the gradient is a
                different size. Set COMPOUNDBARS to 1 to enable compound
                bars.

                Now the maths bit: With these scripts, you have to set the
                scale of the graph manually. Given that some
                spreadsheets that calculate these values tend to make a
                bit of a hash of such things, I though it best to give a
                bit of control. There are two things you need to do:
                Firstly, you set the upper limit of the graph. Generally
                speaking, you'd choose a nice round number that is
                greater than or equal to the maximum value in your
                graph eg. if you had a range of percentages, it's
                sensible to have an upper limit of 100 if you're maximum
                value was 93 or something. If the maximum value was 41,
                you might want to make 50 the upper limit. Enter this
                number into the variable YMAXVAL. Be warned that if you
                set this value inappropriately (ie. too small), then
                your bars will stretch off the edge of the graph, which
                isn't really what you want in your final year project.
                If you make YMAXVAL too large, you'll find that your
                bars will all be extremely small at the bottom of the
                graph. What you want to do is to ensure that you pick a
                value such that all the bars are as tall as they can be
                to fill the area of the graph. The next stage is to set
                the number of ticks for the Y axis. Again, this must be
                chosen judiciously so that wherever possible, each of
                the values shown next to the ticks is a round number.
                So, if we're dealing with percentages, 10 is a good
                number, so that we end up with ten ticks (not including
                zero) each showing ten percent. Likewise, if the maximum
                value was 50 instead of 100, we'd set it to five ticks.
                Again, each of these would show ten percent. By changing
                the size of the graph (using FITSIZEX and FITSIZEY), you
                could make each tick hit one centimetre. Enter this
                value into the variable LINESCALENUMY. You may also add
                standard error bars to your graph. I'm reliably informed
                that this feature is missing from many (if not all)
                Amiga spreadsheets, and while it's unlikely that I'd
                ever use it myself, I'm sure it'll be of use to someone.
                To activate error bars, set STDEV to the standard
                deviation, or to 0 if you don't want error bars.

                Bear in mind that the script is already set up to use
                the font "Rocket" which you'll find on Amiga Format CD
                3. This is primarily because I have set the script so
                that it will produce the same image as the demo picture
                provided (apart from all the gradient fills and
                backdrops of course). However, the script isn't meant to be
                used with just this font. If you don't have this font, then
                by all means change the line which sets the font (there is
                only one) to one you do have. That's the whole idea!

                Note: When you're running this script, be warned that it will
                start looking for a data file. Chances are the location of
                this file will be different when you install the scripts and
                so you'll need to modify the script to reflect this. It's not
                a hard thing to do. Simply look for the line which says
                DATAFILE = "Dh0:T/DSMiscRexxVol3/BarDataFile" and modify the
                contents of the quotes accordingly. Dead easy!

* LineGraph   - This is script was derived from the bar graph script
                (well, mostly from the original version) and so has
                much of the same features as you'll find in NewBarGraph.
                Additionally, you can get the script to draw little boxes at
                individual points, otherwise, it behaves in largely the same
                way as the bar graph script.

                As this script was derived from the bar graph script,
                you'll find that OFFSETX, OFFSETY, FITSIZEX, FITSIZEY,
                LINEGAPX, LINEGAPY, TICKSIZEX, TICKSIZEY, LABELGAPX,
                LABELGAPY, TITLEGAPX, TITLEGAPY, XGRID, YGRID, and
                FRONTGRID all behave identically to those for the bar
                graph, so just for a cop out, I won't bother repeating
                them here. Additionally, you'll find an extra two (count
                'em) variables. If you wish, you can draw a little box
                at wherever a point has been plotted. To do this, set
                SHOWPOINTS to 1 (otherwise leave it at 0). Bear in mind
                that for the example provided, it's not a great deal of
                use because there are 360 points and so they'd appear so
                close together, it's not worth the trouble. However, for
                a small number of points, it' potentially useful. You
                can set the size of the little boxes by changing
                BOXSIZE. Presently, it's 0.2 centimetres.

                As far as setting the scale is concerned, this too works
                just like the bar graph script, with the exception that
                you can set the scale and the number of ticks for both
                the X and Y axis rather than just the Y axis. The same
                rules apply.

                Bear in mind that the script is already set up to use
                the font "Courier" which is a standard Postscript font.
                This is primarily because I have set the script so that it
                will produce the same image as the demo picture provided
                (apart from the backdrops of course). However, the script
                isn't meant to be used with just this font. If you don't
                have this font, then by all means change the line which
                sets the font (there is only one) to one you do have.
                That's the whole idea!

                Note: When you're running this script, be warned that it will
                start looking for a data file. Chances are the location of
                this file will be different when you install the scripts and
                so you'll need to modify the script to reflect this. It's not
                a hard thing to do. Simply look for the line which says
                DATAFILE = "Dh0:T/DSMiscRexxVol3/LineDataFile" and modify the
                contents of the quotes accordingly. Dead easy!

* Table       - This Probably the most useful script in this volume (if
                not all the ones I've done so far), and was much easier
                to write than I first envisaged. It's not brilliant, but
                if you give it a file containing the data (with
                appropriate formatting information), it is possible to
                produce nice tables with less hassle than normal. It
                allows left, centre, and right justification.
                Additionally, it supports vertical alignment, but this
                isn't really anything special when it comes to dealing
                with tall characters.

                To begin with, you may set the margins to be applied to
                the interior of each cell. You may set the left, right,
                top or bottom margins by adjusting CELLLEFTMARGIN,
                CELLRIGHTMARGIN, CELLTOPMARGIN, and CELLBOTTOMMARGIN
                as appropriate. You can choose to show these margins or
                not by altering the value of SHOWMARGINS (set it to 1 to
                show them, or 0 to hide them). The location of the
                actual table on the page (measured from the top left of
                the table) is set with XOFFSET and YOFFSET like most
                other scripts I write. The script has several ways of
                sizing cells. You can either ensure that they all end up
                being the same with or height, or having the width or
                height vary according to the widest or tallest cell in
                each column or row. To make sure that all columns are
                the same width (based upon the widest cell in the entire
                table), set EVENWIDTH to 1 (set it to 0 to allow
                differing widths). To ensure that all rows are the same
                height (based upon the tallest cell in the entire
                table), set EVENHEIGHT to 1 (otherwise, set it to 0 to
                allow differing heights). Finally, as I have mentioned
                before, I'm far from happy at the way the vertical
                alignment works, but I have provided a way of tweaking
                it's (admittedly crap) functionality. CENTRETALLEST can
                be set to one of three values to set the way vertical
                alignment is applied. By setting it to 0, each cell is
                considered individually and so the vertical centre of
                one cell could be quite different from that of another
                cell. The most obvious example would be one cell
                containing a word with a "b" or "g" in it and another
                without. The net effect is that the actual body of the
                characters in the cells containing the word "bigger"
                would be lower down in the cell than a cell containing
                the word "case". This isn't a pleasant effect. In an
                attempt to lessen this effect, you can attempt to align
                the cells in each row vertically by perfoming the
                vertical alignment relative to the tallest cells in the
                row. Therefore, each cell gets treated as if it was as
                tall as the tallest cell. You can activate this by
                setting CENTRETALLEST to 1. This has limited results,
                but in combination with some manipulation of the actual
                vertical alignment control codes, you may be able to get
                away with it. If you're dealing with numbers instead of
                words, you should be OK anyway. The final option is
                setting CENTRETALLEST to 2. This works in a similar way
                to the previous method, except that the cell is measured
                relative to the tallest cell in the entire table rather
                than just that row. It has mainly been added for
                consistency, and it's unlikely to work any better than
                the other options, but by all means try it out if you're
                in difficulty.

                The format of the data file requires some explanation
                because despite being quite simple, on first inspection,
                it looks rather complicated. In essence, each cell is
                defined using the following pattern:

                <HJ><VJ><Text>

                <HJ>   is the horizontal justify setting. This can be
                       either "L", for left alignment, "R" for right
                       alignment, or "C" for centred. This is case
                       insensitive so you don't need to worry about
                       capitalisation.

                <VJ>   is the vertical justify setting. I'm far from
                       happy at the way this works at the moment, but
                       there you go. It stems from a little problem
                       associated with drawing text on the screen.
                       Basically, when the text is aligned, it takes the
                       smallest possible box that surrounds the text
                       (the bounding box) and measures from that.
                       However, this technique falls down when it comes
                       to characters which can stretch upwards (eg. "d")
                       or downwards (eg. "y"). Bummer. If anyone has any
                       clever way for working around this, I'd be
                       interested to hear from you. Anyway, the settings
                       are either "T" for top alignment, "B" for bottom
                       alignment and "M" for middle alignment. Exactly
                       how the alignment is applied depends upon how you
                       set the CENTRETALLEST variable.

                <Text> is simply the text to be placed inside the cell.
                       Generally, this is just plain alphanumeric text
                       with whatever spaces or anything else you like.
                       However, commas are not allowed at the moment (if
                       you would like me to include support for such
                       things, drop me a line). In order to include line
                       breaks, you'll need to include the "\n" control
                       code.

                Here are a couple of quick examples (have a brief look
                at the file "TableDataFile" for a complete example):

                    LMHello        - The word "Hello" left aligned
                                     horizontally, middle aligned
                                     vertically.

                    CTAmigaSoc\nUK - Two lines of text: The first says
                                     "AmigaSoc" and the second, "UK".
                                     Both are centred horizontally, and
                                     aligned to the top vertically.

* NewGrid     - This script contains some some small refinements on my
                original grid script, which has never really been
                anything to write home about. The improvement in this
                version is that you can choose to group rows or columns
                together. Wow.

                As before, you can use XOFFSET and YOFFSET to set the
                position of the grid on the page (measured relative to
                the top left of the grid). The number of cells
                horizontally is set with XCELLS, and the number of cells
                vertically is set with YCELLS. The width and height of
                the entire grid is set using XSIZE and YSIZE. Finally,
                you may wish to group the cells in a certain fashion so
                that you can set the fill and line style of rows or
                columns of cells. By setting GROUPCELLS to 1, all the
                rows get grouped together to make this sort of thing
                easier. You can group columns by setting GROUPCELLS to
                2, or turn grouping off completely by setting it to 0.

If you're quite handy with ARexx, you'll find that I've commented the
code as fully as I can so that it'll be easier for you to figure out
what's going on and tweak it if necessary.

@endnode

@node Distribution "Distribution"

    As with all the software I write, these scripts are FREEWARE. You
can distribute this archive where you like, provided the archive remains
complete and unmodified (I would appreciate being notified if they go on
a coverdisc or CD). You are also free to use these scripts as the basis
of any scripts of your own. If they're for DrawStudio, I'd be interested
to see what you create, although this is by no means essential.

@endnode

@node "Greets" "Greets"

Greetings go out to...

