@endnode

@node "And finally..." "And finally..."

As I've mentioned on countless occasions inside this document, there are
elements of the scripts that I'm not entirely convinced are adequate to
the task. The 3D pie script will draw all the slices and then sort them
into an appropriate order so that the slices don't overlap incorrectly,
but I'm not 100% pleased with the way they are sorted. There may well be
sets of data that cause the slices to be sorted improperly, although
I've yet to get this to happen. The vertical alignment in tables isn't
one of my favourites, either.

Here are some things I'd like to do in future volumes:

*   a GUI. OK, OK, so I keep mentioning this one, but it's something that I
    need to research a little more. Besides, it'll open up the scripts to a
    wider audience. I guess I'll have to learn how to write Installer scripts
    as well one day...

*   Alright, so this is another one I still haven't got round to but a way of
    linking TurboCalc to the bar (see volume one) and the pie chart generation
    scripts would make them a little less cumbersome. I'd also like to
    add the facility to add labels to them. The way things are going so far,
    I might as well write a whole damn spreadsheet of my own anyway!

*   I've been working on a Thumbnails script which allows the
    combination of multiple documents onto one page. It's still far from
    complete and makes things look a bit of a mess at the moment, but
    it's getting there. The present version tends to make a bit of a hash
    of things, but you'll be able to choose how many thumbnails you want per
    page (both across and down) and have the images scaled appropriately, and
    maintaining aspect ratio.

*   I'm also fiddling with a text import script. At the moment, there
    are certain characters which it refuses to import (due to the way
    ARexx works). Once this is fixed, it's yours.

*   Animation. Maybe. OK, well I've written a small script which draws frames
    for a spinning star (which I guess would be useful for anyone sad enough
    to have web pages with "New!" stuffed onto such things to make an
    AnimGIF). Alternatively, I could get the 3D Pie chart to rotate through
    360° if that would ever be of use to anyone... However, much of this stuff
    would require a little hacking using Oliver Grimm's "Recorder" program to
    fill the gaps in DrawStudio's ARexx interface.

...and if you have any further suggestions, get in contact with me.
Also, if you experience any problems when using the scripts, then send
me any datafiles you may have created and mention which settings you
have changed inside the script so that I may reproduce the problem
myself.

    If you feel the urge to contact me, my E-Mail address is:
odin@dcs.qmw.ac.uk. For any non-netsurfers, I can be snail-mailed at 178
Carterhatch Road, Enfield, Middlesex, EN3 5LY, England.

    See you in the next volume!

@endnode
